title: For Sale:  NIB COLT 1911-$850
location: King of Prussia, Southeastern, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
Custom grips-BNIB The pistol that would eventually be named the Colt Commander was Colt's Manufacturing Company's candidate in a U.S. government post-World War II trial to find a lighter replacement for the M1911 pistol that would be issued to officers. Requirements were issued in 1949 that the pistol had to be chambered for 9 mm Parabellum and could not exceed 7 inches in length or weigh more than 25 ounces.[2]
Candidates included Browning Hi-Power variants by Canada's Inglis and Belgium's Fabrique Nationale, and Smith & Wesson's S&W Model 39. Colt entered a modified version of their M1911 pistol that was chambered for 9 mm Parabellum, had an aluminum alloy frame, a short 4.25-inch barrel, and a 9-round magazine. In 1951, Colt moved their candidate into regular production. It was the first aluminum-framed large frame pistol in major production and the first Colt pistol to be originally chambered in 9 mm Parabellum. The first year's production included 45 ACP and 38 Super chamberings.
In 1970, Colt introduced the all-steel "Colt Combat Commander", with an optional model in satin nickel. To differentiate between the two models, the aluminum-framed model was renamed the "Lightweight Commander".

title: For Sale:  COLT 1911 US ARMY (Serial Number 3990) -Turnbull
postcontent: Up for Sale  is the most rare and most valuable pistol from my 1911 collection. It's an original COLT WW1 US ARMY Serial # 3990 There have been millions of 1911's produced in the past decades and to find a Colt for sale with such a low serial number is very very Rare! This pistol was originally built in 1912 (1912 was the first actual year of production for the Model 1911). And what makes this pistol so unique is that it was previously owned by Brigadier General S.W. Fitzgerald of the US Army Air Corps,This pistol has been fully restored by Turnbull Manufacturing Company. It is currently in (like new) condition, unfired since the day that it left the Turnbull gun shop, with no marks and no scratches, it's about as beautiful as they come! This pistol also comes with a (collector's guide) 1911 book showing the previous ownership by Lieutenant S.W. Fitzgerald. It also comes with one 7 round magazine (keyhole style). This is an all around great looking pistol with a long history within the US Military. After all restorations completed by Doug Turnbull,

title: For Sale:  Madsen Light Machine Gun (Semi Only)
postcontent:
This is a semi-auto build of the venerable Madsen LMG. The Madsen was the first ever light machine gun design done by the Danish army prior to WW1. It's most common uses were by the German army in WW2 after the capture of Denmark. It uses a falling block action which is very unique as opposed to blowback or piston. This model is chambered in 8mm mauser.  Any time im at the range I always draw a crowd. 

This is a non-nfa weapon and is perfectly legal to own. It is Semi ONLY - made by MMC with the ATF compliance letter.

Here is a video of it firing: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NDwW8jVZ8p4

Completely functional -never had a jam, misfire, feed or ejection issue - runs just as well as your AK.

Very rare piece, price is firm - only trade interest is a semi-auto bren. Only selling to purchase a Bren to complete my WW2 British collection.

title: For Sale:  Collectible, Hard to Find Ammo - Part 1
postcontent:
Hey everyone. I've just about finished selling my life long collection of military small arms from around the world so now I've opened up my ammo & accessories safe and I'll be selling it's contents as I have time. 

All of this ammo has been stored in my air conditioned home inside a dehumidified safe.  

A few things to keep in mind: First most of this ammo was originally designed for either military or LE use, and a lot of it is either steel jacketed, steel core or both. So any ammo I describe as magnetic means that it will potentially penetrate targets much deeper than standard commercial ammo. Therefore please be extra cautious with your backstop if you decide to shoot any of it. I feel quite sure that it all will fire so be careful. Second any of the tracer ammo can and will start fires. So again please use with all due caution. Here is the ammo in this lot: 

(2) 40 round boxes Czech military 7.62x25 - brass case, corrosive & magnetic (in this case steel core). Ammo is loaded on eight round chargers. All 7.62x25 penetrates well but this ammo takes that to a whole new level with it's steel core. Extreme caution necessary. $40 for the 80 rounds. 

(1) 50 round box 9mm Kurz - another name for .380 ACP. Ammo made by Lapua in 1942. It's brass case, corrosive and in incredibly good shape for it's age. $25 

(2) 50 round sealed boxes of 9mm Steyr caliber by Hirtenberger. Brass case, non corrosive & magnetic. Asking $120 for both boxes - super rare ammo. 1 sold 1 available 

(2) 25 round boxes GECO 7.65mm or .32 ACP here. Ammo is brass case, non corrosive and very magnetic so it penetrates like crazy. $30 for both boxes. Sold

(2) 25 round boxes S&B 6.35mm or .25 ACP here. Brass case, non corrosive and magnetic. So again it will penetrate much more than any current commercial ammo. $25 for both boxes. 

(1) partial box of the old Winchester yellow & red box .38 Special 158 grain lead bullet. 10 rounds remaining. Box is in fair shape and ammo is excellent. $10 

(4) 25 round boxes Santa Barbara (Spain) 9mm Largo. Brass case, brass plated bullet & non corrosive. Hard to find ammo that is perfect for your Astra & Star pistols, Destroyer carbines and many more. $70 for all 4 boxes. 

(2) 50 round boxes of Hirtenberger 9mm LE ammo. Ammo has a 100 grain copper jacketed, truncated cone, soft point bullet. Ammo is non corrosive and it's loaded to very high velocities for 9mm Luger ammo. Head stamp is +P+. It's safe to use in well constructed modern pistols by GLOCK, Colt, Ruger, S&W, SIG, etc. However it should never be used in older or poor quality pistols as doing so could be very unsafe. This was imported in very limited quantities and is tough to find today. It's certainly not practice ammo, but rather what you'd want to use when your life could depend on it. $100 for both boxes. 1 sold 1 available

I have additional quantities of some of the ammo listed above but not all. So just ask if you are looking for more than is listed. 

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Rare, Collectible, Hard to Find Ammo - Part 2
postcontent:
Hey everyone. I've just about finished selling my life long collection of military small arms from around the world so now I've opened up my ammo & accessories safe and I'll be selling it's contents as I have time.  

All of this ammo has been stored in my air conditioned home inside a dehumidified safe.   

A few things to keep in mind: First most of this ammo was originally designed for either military or LE use, and a lot of it is either steel jacketed, steel core or both. So any ammo I describe as magnetic means that it will potentially penetrate targets much deeper than standard commercial ammo. Therfore please be extra cautious with your backstop if you decide to shoot any of it. I feel quite sure that it all will fire so be careful. Second any of the tracer ammo can and will start fires. So again please use with all due caution. Here is the ammo in this lot:  

(2) 20 round boxes 6.5 x 55 Swedish Mauser. Brass case, non corrosive & magnetic. Very clean military surplus ammo. $35 for both boxes. 

(2) 20 round boxes 6.5 x 55 Swedish Mauser with wooden bullet. This ammo is intended as a blank round but requires a special adapter to shred the bullet at the muzzle. Without this adapter the wooden bullet is dangerous and could be fatal at close range so use caution when firing. $15 for both boxes. 

(5) 10 round boxes of Nazi 8x56R for use in Steyr Straight Pull rifles & carbines. This ammo is brass case, corrosive and magnetic. It's unbelievably clean for being made in 1938. This ammo is truly collectible and the box plus every round is stamped with the Nazi War Eagle. Each box has 10 rounds loaded on 2 stripper clips. These clips & empty boxes sell on Ebay for as much or more than I'm asking for the real live ammo. Price is $20 a box or $80 for all five. 

(1) 50 rounds Kynoch 7mm Mauser loaded on 5 round chargers. Ammo is brass case, corrosive & very magnetic. This box is unopened so I did not want to disturb it. However I have a partial box of the same ammo and it's unbelievably clean... looks like it was just made, but it was actually produced in January 1938, and it's noted right on the box. Vintage Kynoch is among the most collectible ammo available. Asking $100 for the box. 

(1) 100 round bulk box of 7mm Mauser made by FN Belgium in 1936. Ammo was made for lVenezuela, and it's brass case, corrosive and very magnetic.This ammo is also in unbelievable condition for it's age. Cases are bright and there are no signs or corrosion or deterioration at all. Very collectible and perfect to display with your South American Mauser(s).  $75 for the box. 

I do have additional quantities of some, but not all of the ammo listed above. So just ask if you are looking for more. 

Thanks for looking.

This VZ-52 is a 1955, chambered in the VERY unique 7.62x45mm round.
The bore is EXCELLENT, a lot of these rifles have "sewer pipe" barrels from the corrosive ammo.. how ever this barrel is bright,with strong lands and grooves, no pitting or frosting. 
Functions and fires wonderfully (A lot of the FTF issues with these rifles are from the ammo, NOT the rifle.. Hard primers and time )

Over all excellent rifle, I have a few more of these rifles and they are a joy to shoot
